This paper discusses privacy risks associated with browser extensions and web logins, which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The study also involves analyzing user behavior and identifying users based on their extensions and logins, which could be categorized under social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper also discusses the trade-off between privacy and the usefulness of privacy extensions, which could be categorized under cyber-physical systems (cs.CY) or human-computer interaction (cs.HC). Finally, the paper proposes countermeasures to address the privacy risks, which could be categorized under programming languages (cs.PL) as it involves developing solutions to a specific problem.
